1Ô∏è‚É£ What is CloudWatch?

CloudWatch is AWS‚Äôs monitoring and observability service.
It collects metrics, logs, and events from AWS resources and applications so you can monitor, alert, and troubleshoot your systems.

2Ô∏è‚É£ What can CloudWatch monitor?

1Ô∏è‚É£ Metrics ‚Üí Numerical data over time

CPU usage, memory, disk I/O, network traffic

EC2, RDS, Lambda, ELB, custom metrics

2Ô∏è‚É£ Logs ‚Üí Application or system logs

Rails / Phoenix app logs

Error logs, access logs

3Ô∏è‚É£ Events ‚Üí AWS system or custom events

Auto Scaling events, EC2 state changes

3Ô∏è‚É£ Why use CloudWatch?

Visibility ‚Üí Know how your system is performing

Alerts ‚Üí Get notified if CPU, memory, or errors exceed threshold

Troubleshooting ‚Üí Analyze logs to find issues

Automation ‚Üí Trigger actions via CloudWatch Alarms

4Ô∏è‚É£ CloudWatch Components
Component	Purpose
Metrics	Track numeric performance (CPU, memory, requests/sec)
Logs	Store application and system logs
Alarms	Notify when metrics cross thresholds (e.g., CPU > 80%)
Dashboards	Visualize metrics & logs in one place
Events	Respond to system or custom events
5Ô∏è‚É£ Example Use Case

Scenario: Rails/Phoenix app on EC2 + RDS

Metrics: CPU usage of EC2, read/write IOPS of RDS

Logs: Application errors (log/production.log)

Alarms: CPU > 80% ‚Üí send Slack / trigger Auto Scaling

Dashboard: Combine EC2 + RDS metrics for overall health

6Ô∏è‚É£ Pros & Cons (Simple Version)
‚úÖ Pros

Centralized monitoring for AWS resources

Works with custom application metrics

Can trigger automated actions

Scales with AWS infrastructure

‚ùå Cons

AWS-only by default (requires extra setup for on-prem)

Cost increases with high log retention or metrics

